==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Whisk
<hw>Whisk</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Whist</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>A game at cards; whist.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Taylor (1630).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whisk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Whisk
<hw>Whisk</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Probably for <ets>wisk</ets>, and of
Scand. origin; cf. Icel. <ets>visk</ets> a wisp; akin to Dan.
<ets>visk</ets>, Sw. <ets>viska</ets>, D. <ets>wisch</ets>, OHG.
<ets>wisc</ets>, G. <ets>wisch</ets>. See <er>Wisp</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of whisking; a rapid, sweeping motion, as of
something light; a sudden motion or quick puff.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This first sad <qex>whisk</qex>⟦br⟧
Takes off thy dukedom; thou art but an earl.</q> <rj><qau>J.
Fletcher.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small bunch of grass, straw, twigs, hair, or the
like, used for a brush; hence, a brush or small besom, as of broom
corn.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A small culinary instrument made of wire, or the
like, for whisking or beating eggs, cream, etc.</def>
<rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A kind of cape, forming part of a woman's
dress.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My wife in her new lace <qex>whisk</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pepys.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>An impertinent fellow.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A plane used by coopers for evening
chines.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whisk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Whisk
<hw>Whisk</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Whisked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Whisking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. Dan. <ets>viske</ets>, Sw.
<ets>viska</ets>, G. <ets>wischen</ets>, D. <ets>wisschen</ets>. See
<er>Whisk</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To sweep, brush, or agitate, with a light, rapid
motion; <as>as, to <ex>whisk</ex> dust from a table; to <ex>whisk</ex>
the white of eggs into a froth.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move with a quick, sweeping motion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that walks in gray, <qex>whisking</qex> his riding rod.</q>
<rj><qau>J. Fletcher.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I beg she would not impale worms, nor <qex>whisk</qex> carp out of
one element into another.</q> <rj><qau>Walpole.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whisk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Whisk
<hw>Whisk</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To move nimbly at with velocity;
to make a sudden agile movement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whisker</ent>⟦br⟧
